"meanings":["English: mainly a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a wood, from Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘wood’ (Old English <i>wudu</i>). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, such as French   Bois   and Polish   Les  .","English: in a few cases, a nickname for an eccentric or perhaps a violent person, from Middle English <i>wode</i> ‘frenzied, wild’ (Old English <i>wōd</i>).","Americanized form of French   Gadbois  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Woode","meanings":["(2007: 216; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Wood  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 312, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]},{"name":"Bois","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alcide, Antoine, Donat, Marcel, Ovide, Ovila, Raoul, Serge.","French: topographic name for someone living or working in a wood, from (Old) French <i>bois</i> ‘wood’ (from Late Latin <i>boscum</i> ‘bush, shrub, undergrowth’, of ancient Germanic origin), or a habitational name from (Le) Bois, the name of several places in various parts of France. This surname is also found in Haiti. Compare   Debois   and the most frequent French form   Dubois  . Compare also   Boie  ,   Boies  , and   Boyce  .","English: variant of   Boyce   and   Boyes  ."]},{"name":"Woods","meanings":["English: variant of   Wood   with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish: adopted as a translation of <b>Ó Cuill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Coll</i>’ (see   Quill  ), or in Ulster of <b>Mac Con Coille</b> ‘son of <i>Cú Choille</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘hound of the wood’, which has also been mistranslated   Cox  , as if formed with <i>coileach</i> ‘cock, rooster’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Wood was born in 1460, in Wybunbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Denes or Diones in 1485, in Sanderstead, Surrey, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1528, in Enfield, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1460–1528":"1460–1528","1460–1530":"1460–1530","1485–1584":"1485–1584","1500–1571":"1500–1571","1509–1560":"1509–1560","1500":"1500","1530":"1530","1485":"1485","1584":"1584","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","1460":"1460","1509":"1509","1528":"1528","about 1509":"umbes 1509","Dorking, Surrey, England":"Dorking, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Godstone, Surrey, England":"Godstone, Surrey, England","Sanderstead, Surrey, England":"Sanderstead, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Culmstock, Devon, England":"Culmstock, Devon, England","Wybunbury, Cheshire, England":"Wybunbury, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Enfield, Middlesex, England":"Enfield, Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1460–1528":"1460–1528","1460–1530":"1460–1530","1485–1584":"1485–1584","1500–1571":"1500–1571","1509–1560":"1509–1560","1500":"1500","1530":"1530","1485":"1485","1584":"1584","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","1460":"1460","1509":"1509","1528":"1528","about 1509":"noin 1509","Dorking, Surrey, England":"Dorking, Surrey, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Godstone, Surrey, England":"Godstone, Surrey, England","Sanderstead, Surrey, England":"Sanderstead, Surrey, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Culmstock, Devon, England":"Culmstock, Devon, England","Wybunbury, Cheshire, England":"Wybunbury, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"